===Verb===
{{en-verb|inferr}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To introduce (something) as a reasoned [[conclusion]]; to [[conclude]] by [[reason]]ing or [[deduction]], as from [[premise]]s or [[evidence]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#* '''2010''', "Keep calm, but don't carry on", ''The Economist'', 7 Oct 2010:
#*: It is dangerous to '''infer''' too much from martial bluster in British politics: at the first hint of trouble, channelling Churchill is a default tactic for beleaguered leaders of all sorts.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[lead]] to (something) as a [[consequence]]; to [[imply]]. (Now often considered incorrect, especially with a person as subject.) {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Florio Montaigne Essayes|chapter=3|book=II|passage=These and a thousand like propositions, which concurre in this purpose, do evidently '''inferre''' {{transterm|sonnent|lang=frm}} some thing beyond patient expecting of death it selfe to be suffered in this life{{nb...}}.}}
#* Shakespeare
#*: This doth '''infer''' the zeal I had to see him.
#* Sir Thomas More
#*: The first part is not the proof of the second, but rather contrariwise, the second '''inferreth''' well the first.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[cause]], [[inflict]] (something) {{m|en|upon}} or {{m|en|to}} someone. {{defdate|16th-18th c.}}
#* '''1596''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''The Faerie Queene'', VI.8:
#*: faire Serena{{...}}fled fast away, afeard / Of villany to be to her '''inferd'''{{nb...}}.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[introduce]] (a subject) in speaking, writing etc.; to [[bring in]]. {{defdate|16th–18th c.}}
#* Shakespeare
#*: Full well hath Clifford played the orator, / '''Inferring''' arguments of mighty force.

====Usage notes====
There are two ways in which the word "infer" is sometimes used as if it meant "[[imply]]". "[[implication|Implication]]" is done by a person when making a "[[statement]]", whereas "inference" is done to a proposition after it had already been made or assumed. Secondly, the word "infer" can sometimes be used to mean "[[allude]]" or "[[express]]" in a suggestive manner rather than as a direct "statement". Using the word "infer" in this sense is now generally considered incorrect. [http://www.askoxford.com/betterwriting/classicerrors/confused/?view=uk] [http://englishplus.com/grammar/00000232.htm]

